  "text": "The N 2 adsorption/desorption isotherms provide a textural characterization of the BC adsorbent. The parameters obtained were the specific surface area, total pore volume, micropore volume, and average pore diameter. Figure 1 shows the N 2 adsorption and desorption Langmuir isotherm for the BC. According to IUPAC classification, the observed isotherm profile indicated a Type IV isotherm which is typical for mesoporous materials. Furthermore, the isotherm also has a Type H3 hysteresis which is associated with the predominance of pores in parallel plates form. From pore size distribution, it can be seen that BC surface is essentially mesoporous, since it has high incidence of pore diameters between 20 and 100 Å [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Table 1 presents the textural properties of the adsorbent. The average pore diameter of BC was 99.5 Å . The result of the application of the BJH method showed a larger amount of mesopore volume (20 Å < pore diameter < 500 Å ), representing approximately 98% of the total pore volume.",
